content:
This place serves the most innovative prata creations, as well as fantastic well-rounded normal pratas with delicious drinks.

Their pratas are always sweet, eggy and delicious, their curries a mild spicy, sweet, milky and full of flavour, their murtaburger is the bomb, their tandoori chicken murtabaks are always juicy and never dry, their poached egg hollandaise sauce and ham combo is delicious, their portobello mushroom and mozzarella cheese pratas defy all expectations while their briyani is soft, dripping with a melt in your mouth lamb shank.

If you don't have a quirk for crispy pratas, or a preference for spicy curries and just don't know where to go - this place has the quality and variety down pat. Their kopi cinos and the cinos are super yummy too.

content:
My husband found us a $50 cash voucher for the price of $35 on Chope (valid between 11:30am-12:00pm Mondays-Friday). Timeline was tight but we were in the area so it worked out. *Note: We were informed the voucher would work for everything on the menu except the Peking duck platters.*

We arrived around noon on a Thursday. It was busy but we were able to get a table without making a reservation ahead of time. The food was pretty good. The har gow, siew mai, xiao long bao, bbq pork buns were all really tasty! Some of their dishes were on the saltier end - especially the chicken feet. The custard lava buns were really delicious! It was a lovely blend of pineapple bun exterior with custard filling on the inside.

I was really impressed with their service. Our cups were continuously re-filled before it was even empty! Our plates were changed about 2-3 times to ensure we had a clean plate for whatever dish we were having. So thoughtful!

The only thing that caught me off guard was we had to pay to pack the leftovers. This wasn‚Äôt AYCE so it was strange to me that it would cost $1/item to pack things to-go. This has never happened to me in the history of dining out.

content:
A true hidden gem!  Tucked away discreetly on the second floor of a shop lot on Purvis street, you won‚Äôt notice it unless you go looking.

Hands down, probably the best meal I‚Äôve had in Singapore.  We started with the Hamachi Carpaccio that was topped with generous truffles shaving and ikura, drizzled with truffle shoyu - the yellow tail was so fresh and every bite was simply a flavour bomb hit!  Next came the Tanoke Beef Bowl (rib eye).  It was a masterpiece, where the meat just melts in your mouth, so tender, juicy and cooked just right. The creamy yolk from the onsen egg made it the perfect sauce to go with the Niigata rice.  Soooo yumms.

They also do Sake pairing but not much of a drinker‚Ä¶. But definitely a must if you are a sake lover.

Also love the sleek decor & vibe, making it a great place for date nights or girlie get together.  Staff were all attentive and ready to serve.

Can‚Äôt wait to come back and try more items on the menu.  Highly recommend!!

I can‚Äôt believe that I have not put up a review of Lotus Vegetarian! We have been enjoying their food since 2020 when I took out from their Ubi kitchen. And of course proceeded to enjoy the lovely and bright ambience at their Novena restaurant when it opened.

Today, I stopped by to pick up some dinner. Decided to try something new, cos always eat the same reliable favourites - dry laksa, all the tim sum esp fupijuan (bean curd sheet roll), chasiewpow, jianpow, shuijing pow.

So we had dry laksa (haha couldn‚Äôt resist), French beans with radish, mapo doufu and cordecep soup. Everything is as delicious at home as when eaten on site. 10% discount for taking out too!

Update 10/7/21
Taking the chance to dine in before 5 people can eat together‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs quiet tonite on sat nite with less than half the tables filled. But I‚Äôm sure business will pick up once HA is lifted, so gotta book or wait for seat.

Had the nasi lemak and mutton curry. Both were delicious. Nasi lemak was tasty without being overbearingly rich. Bleu pea rice was fluffy, chilli was sweet and spicy, fried fish pieces were fragrant, lightly blanched lady fingers were dressed in chicken rice chilli, and fried ‚Äúchicken‚Äù pieces (bean strips) were crispy and tantalizing!  Again The mutton curry was tasty but light. There was a generous amount of potatoes and ‚Äúmutton‚Äù pieces in the soupy but not diluted curry which we drank up!

content: It was a horrendous first dining experience at this notably renowned venue for Teochew cuisine. Regrettably I should have known from the deteriorating quality mentioned in earlier Google reviews. From the start, we had made a reservation via phone call for 9 persons, but we were shown to a table for 8 persons (7+1) When we questioned about that, the lady serving us had no answer and basically just replied that it‚Äôs okay they would add one more seat to a smaller looking table.  It was strange but I thought nothing of it until almost towards the end of the meal when we were again asked whether they could serve mixed fruits platter. That was when it hit me that they had mixed us up with another bunch of guests. Despite repeated complaints, none of the staff looked sincerely apologetic and merely was in a rush to turn over the table for the second round of diners. Apart from that, the quality of food served tonight was not outstanding, and service was rushed and nobody bothered changing plates or pouring tea till we asked for it. The pomfret appeared to be not cooked well, there was redness and toughness in some part of the meat. It is definitely not a place worth the premium paid for food, service, decoration or anything at all. Atmosphere wise, the place was noisy and warm with spot lights all over and little aircon. It was supposed to be a nice welcoming dinner for our guests but tonight it was nothing short of a disaster with the premium paid for dinner; total damage (bill) being more than 500 dollars. Consider seriously, if you really want to come to dine (unless you really have the cash to spare or prefer to take photos of the food presentation). Note: there was no service recovery done at all.

content: Went to Jurong Point's outlet on a Sunday. Was my 1st time and probably the last. My family of 6 were not let in to the restaurant when there's clearly an unoccupied table for 6 there. Had to talk to the worker and reason with him as to why he couldn't let us sit at that table. His reason being that table is too close to other tables (safety distancing measures) but all other occupied tables with customers seated are close to each other too. It made no sense and the worker finally let us sit there only when we said that we would like to speak to the manager about this matter. Upon sitting at the table, we were not given the menu after a good 5 minutes and had to approach the waiter to be given the menu. The waiter told us that the order is to be done via scanning a QR code but the QR code slip was not given to us. We were cluelessly finding the QR inside the menu when it was actually a printed QR code slip which is supposed to be given by the waiter. So we had to ask for the menu and also the QR code to be given to us. The food arrived fast but the soup tasted bland. Even the soup with the "richest" taste option selected tasted bland. The soup was barely warm too, not hot like a soup that is freshly cooked. The only thing that was nice were the onsen eggs.  Basically an unpleasant experience going there.

restaurant name: Crystal Jade La Mian Xiao Long Bao
content: Crystal jade jiangnan specialises in la mien and does it well. The menu also includes some cantonese cuisine and dim sum.  Some lovely dishes that I would go back for more would by the seafood crispy noodles and multi grain fried rice and the xiao long bao. The chunky seafood with its gravy was thoughtfully set aside to prevent the crispy noodles from turning soft too quickly. I like generous chunks of fish squid mushrooms prawns and a dash of leafy green that made this dish a seafood haven. It was well executed without being overly salty. That goes the same for the multi grain brown rice that was well cooked and presented in a stone bowl. Absolutely delicious and very healthy indeed! They have a spread of various types of xiaolong bao but I would recommend the normal flavour that allows you to experience the delicate yet flavorful pork infused with a delicious broth and sealed within the dumpling.  I wasn't too impressed with the lao sao bao which had very little filling making it rather dry;  and the ying yang steamed dumpling that had the skin too thick and the filling devoid of flavour. Service is alright though it would be ideal to make reservations if the group is large due to the small seating area.

content: I can imagine the fuss with wanting to taste nostalgia. Other than that, I'll say,  take your money elsewhere. We were there on a weekday evening and there were about 5-6 customers ahead of us in the queue. We got to order in about 10 minutes and I'd have to commend the kitchen for delivering at such record speed. After ordering, we waited for about 8 minutes before our orders were ready. The Mushroom Sauce Chicken Chop ($6.50) had a piece of flabby skin that was not charred to extract at least 30% of the fat. It was just cooked and not actually the way I prefer to eat my chicken skin. The piece of chicken, although tender and juicy, had quite a fowl-like odour which reminded me of chicken chops at cook houses. I have no idea how this store used to taste like, but I do not like their style of cooking now. Fries were just tasteless, not salty and blah. The slice of bread although nicely toasted, had the taste of Planta which I hate. The Grilled Salmon ($9) was under seasoned with a strong fishy taste but the doneness was just right. It was soft within and melted in the mouth, not overdone and flaky at all. The worst of the lot would have to be the Butter Garlic Lamb Chops ($12). We got a sinewy cut of the meat and the butter garlic compound was an absolute horror. It was made of Planta margarine and dried rosemary..nothing in it had the taste of butter or garlic! All in all, it's great if you miss the taste of 90's style western food at an inflated price. Otherwise, it's just cheap ingredients, canned beans and junk sold at a premium price. I could walk over to the coffeeshop next door and get a chicken chop at $5. Perhaps our taste buds have evolved and we're now spoilt for choices when it comes to customizable fancy sides like sauteed mushrooms, roasted sweet potatoes, mac n cheese and the like.

Boss lady advised to call to check if you want dry version later part of the day, as the dried prawn always sold out early.

content:
If you're a Thai food lover then I urge you to not missed out this authentic Thai food stall that is hidden right in the heart of toa payoh central. I have seen this stall around recently as it was opened not long ago after covid period. I think around May if I'm not wrong? The main chef is from Thailand so please be assured you're getting real authentic Thai food! This stall is located right in J99 coffeeshop together my favourite chicken rice stall... I have been eating chicken rice all along and haven't been able to try this Thai stall until today.

Their menu is very extensive and it all the usual Thai favourites can be found right in their menu. Their price are also super affordable and most of all, it is very very valuable for money. Basil pork goes for 5.50 and it comes with egg. You can also try out their basil prawn which is super good as well. Their prawns are not those small little shrimps as they used medium prawns which are fresh and crunchy.

The aunties here are also super friendly and courteous so don't be afraid to ask for their recommendations if you're a first timer like me. I will be back again to try their other dishes such as phad Thai and Tom yum soup. Hope they will survive in the long run as this stall is quite small and if you don't look around carefully, you might missed their stall as there are quite a nunber of stall in this coffeeshop.

content:
Food: 10/10! All that we have tried so far were delicious and veggies had good wokhei flavor. Haven't had a disappointing dish so far.

Service: 10/10 as well!
Ordered via Deliveroo last month but the stall was sold out on many items already. One of their staff called me and asked if it's possible to replace my orders with those available. When the food came, my green curry chicken was missing. Deliveroo didn't do anything, told me to Contact the stall so I tried to call their number online but it goes to their boss's number who was not at outlet. Their boss was apologetic and offered to give additional item on next order. Next order came around and indeed I was given extra fishcake on top of my orders. Had a small chat with the boss and definitely very friendly and keen on providing good food. Good service.

Sadly, my curry was still not refunded via Deliveroo, but not their fault... Was deliveroo slow processing.

content:
Fantastic meal here at A-Roy Thai. Was a Sunday night around 8+ but the restaurant was still bustling, will recommend to make a reservation if you come during the peak dinner timings.

The meal itself was delightful, not the regular local style Thai food but according to my gf, it had more Northern Thai influences to it but more importantly, done well.

Prices are not cheap, 1 appetizer, 3 mains and 2 drinks set us back around $90+ compared to the regular Thai food places but this is money well spent.

The lemongrass salad was fantastic, a must order (the staff don't tell you but you eat it with the wrap on the side). Tom yum kung was good, not mind blowing but definitely above average. The Grilled Pork was done very differently, in a good way, a spicier way actually.

The service was friendly and the food came out surprisingly fast. The grilled pork took a bit longer but the rest of the dishes came first.

Would definitely return! But have to budget myself else it'd really burn a huge hole in my pocket!

content:
I have to say the food here is super inconsistent.

My first time ordering:
Got their beef donburi with broccoli, salmon Miso soup and mentaiko sauce.
Beef was good as it had flavourful and wasn't too dry. Broccoli we're kinda disappointing as it was just plain broccoli boiled in water and there were only 2 pieces. For the salmon Miso soup, it tasted good without being overly salty. Mentaiko sauce is spicier that your regular mentaiko and somehow the mentaiko is milder.
Overall I enjoyed my meal and this taste better than Yoshinoya if you need comparison. I also like how their portion is slightly larger.

Update: I ordered another 3 more times from them so a total of 4 times on 4 different days.

For my 2nd order I was super impressed. They added more seaweed to their don And the flavours were good. Only sad thing was the onsen egg with the broken yolk. But other than that it was a wonderful meal.

For my 3rd order, it was HORRIBLE, just look at the pictures attached. The rice was just lump together and mushy. How could they actually serve such rice to their customers? The boiled egg though perfectly cooked was just roughly handle, look at the broken egg white. For the protein this time, I got their wagyu flank beef and boy was that a mistake. Tough, flavourless piece of meat with some parts having some black pepper taste. For the price I was charged, I am SUPER DISAPPOINTED with this meal

For my 4th order which was during the week dine-in was allowed, I decided to give them another chance. Let me say I TOTALLY regretted my choice. Rice was AGAIN lumpy and mushy but this time it wasn't that bad only like 1/2 of the rice had this issue. This was during dinner time. What is wrong with them? Can't they even get the basic right anymore? Also I got the SALMON soup which this time apparently didn't contain any SALMON. Instead, was replaced with a small cube of tofu and a lot of kelp.

content:
Food - 3.8/5
Waiting time - 1/5
Service - 1/5

Food:
More affordable than putien restaurant. Taste decent, like any good standard zhi char stall, but wont say extraordinary. Menu was comprehensive.

Waiting time:
Dabaoed food for Sunday dinner. Placed order at 6.10pm, which i thought was pretty early. But only received the food at 7.10pm and after atleast 5 times of asking to check on my order.

Service:
Understandable that shop is crowded and everyone was busy. But when i keep asking the helpers to check on my order, they always ask the main guy directing the flow, and in the end no reply was given. Went directly to the main guy to ask to check, he didn't even look at the orders he had in hand and told me to come back 15min, and say its cooking already. Went back 10min later to check again, and asked if the dishes even started cooking. And he finally went to take a look and hurried his chefs on my order. Just felt he should be honest about the situation. If the dishes were not cooked, just be truthful. At least we can better estimate our own waiting time and not be a fool standing there and waiting. Also they seem to have another order line which people call in and ordered, and paid when they come to collect. Those orders and those eat in orders seemed to be prioritied compared us who took the effort to walk in and order, and even paid upfront. Really upset about this whole situation.

Those who intend to try the stall can perhaps catch them at the off peak hours, or try calling in to see if u can pre order. All the best.

content:
After watching the review of a food vlogger we decided to try.

They go by weight and it's not the cheapest.  If you want to really get your money's worth, just take all meat, seafood and mushroom. Forget anything green.

None of the food is labelled so, choosing the meat is just a matter of fatty or lean.

They are very responsive on the telegram chat so just check with them for any queries.

Ideally, start your meal no later than 6.30 pm.  The queue gets out of control towards the night. We stepped in at 6pm and we were eating in less than 15 minutes.

The spice level of "low" is equal to "Wei la" outside.

The fried potato, is no different from potato chips, nothing really amazing, maybe potato chips are cheaper.

The fried lotus root was interesting. Since we do not find the fried lotus root chips outside easily, it is worth a return trip. Our nitpick is, they just fry the items without seasoning, no Cajun powder no salt n pepper. (OK maybe the dory had salt)  perhaps my expectation were shaped by LokLok and therefore too high.

I would really have preferred if they deep fried then somehow integrated the mala sauce with the fried items, maybe offer a dip. Maybe I am too influenced by loklok.

The scrambled eggs are just scrambled eggs without any seasoning.

Every other item was typical of a Mala shop. Either you agree with the taste or disagree. I agree with the taste.

The green and brown drink is Thai milk tea. The green one seems to be Thai milk tea with jasmine green tea. They are not really strong brew, but worth the $2.50 price tag. Probably one of the cheapest Thai milk tea.

There is a strange smell on the tray, but small matter, just put it away.

Unlike many other eating places in NTU there is no student price for flashing your student card here.

This place is not worth a detour. It is worth trying if you are in the area or you drive.

content:
Went with my family just before the lockdown and tried their chicken and mutton briyani, and chicken murtabak. Best I ever tried!

The mutton was so tender that it kinds of "melt in the mouth". The flavour of the rice was made just right (does not have that overwhelming spice taste). When the mutton, rice and gravy were eaten together, it gave a homely and familar feeling which is satisfying.

The chicken briyani was good as well. The chicken meat was tender and not dry.

The chicken murtabak had a special taste. It was slightly cripsy on the outside and had a slight lingering sweet taste. I like it!

It was an air-conditioned and nice place. The kitchen was properly separated from the dining area so my clothes didn't have that food smell or feel after the meal.

The individual serving size was adequate and will satisfy the general population.

Would really like to try how their pratas as well if I had more stomach capacity but will definitely visit them again (when the situation allows it)!

content:
Recently visit and I must say if you want authentic Thai food to satisfy Thai food craving, here is the place! I highly recommend here and I love their quality dishes are all at affordable price plus the staffs are very friendly.

What I have,

Soi Aroy Signature Mixed Platter.
Comes with Moo Ping (pork skewers), Lemongrass Chicken and Grilled Pork Cheeks that are marinated for 24 hours. Once served the staff will torch the pork cheek on the spot to give that smokiness and melt in mouth goodness once you bite on while the lemongrass chicken and mooping are grilled to tender perfection.

Crispy Papaya Salad with deep fried soft shell crab!! This dish was probably the most unique out of all the dishes tried. A unique rendition of the familiar papaya salad that been battered and deep fried till crispy and atop deep fried soft shell crab. Have it together with the tangy and nutty dipping sauce, I'm in heaven.

Crispy Omelette With Crab Meat.
This is another of the stand-out dishes to me.
The fried egg is not only airy and fluffy, but very crispy and not being in any way greasy as well. The added crab meat atop, adds a distinct note of crustacean sweetness to the omelette and the crab meat itself is fresh.

Thai Steamed Seabass with Lime & Chilli.
Ocean fresh Seabass steamed in special lime and chilli sauce topped with SuperThai special sauce. I like you can opt for fish fillet or the entire seabass. Fresh, tender meat paired with the spicy sauce that keeps me eating non stop.

Seafood Tom Yum Soup.
It blew me away with its depth and bold flavours. Sour and spicy which goes perfectly with rice and the seafood is really fresh here.

Claypot Vermicelli with Prawns.
The prawns are fresh and succulent and the vermicelli is bursting with flavour from having absorbed the sauce. Pack a flavourful punch.

Fresh Oyster.
I'm very lucky that I went day they have fresh oyster and is so fresh when you dip with their sauce, you in ocean heaven!

Mango Sticky Rice.
Hard to give this Thai dessert amiss. I love this as it has the perfect firmness and sweetness of the Thai Mango thay went perfectly well with the perfect texture of the glutinous rice and coconut milk. This dessert is highly commendable.

Red Ruby with Coconut Icecream.
Coconut Icecream on top shaved ice, drizzled with sweet red syrup and fresh coconut milk. Topped with red rubies that gives a chewy crunch.

The Thai Iced Tea here is a must DRINK. Not too sweet yet strong enough taste of the tea aroma.

A place worth keep coming back to.

content:
Checked out this western stall that specialized in smoked meat at one of the coffeeshop of the industrial area in AMK street 62. I was there around 2pm and the lunch crowd has already died down. We order the meat platter for 2 which comes with 2 choices of sides (SGD$25), creamy pasta (SGD$5.50) and a Agilo olio (SGD$4.50).

Food didn‚Äôt take long to be served. The meat platter consisted of smoked brisket, pork belly and turkey.The sides were garlic mash and fries. Meat was average to be honest, Mash was bland, could do with more seasoning. Pasta was quite decent though, I liked the idea of having an onsen egg to go with the pasta.

Will I come all the way for this? Probably not. But in general, for the portion wise, it‚Äôs quite value for money.

content: Heng Hwa Fried Bee Hoon was light and clean - though I can feel that some people may think of it as tasteless. But honestly speaking, their chilli is so shiok that even if you are on 'bee hoon too is tasteless' camp, just smother some of their chilli on and you will be converted instantly. Another dish that I would highly recommend is Stir Fried Sliced Yam - the combination of light crispy batter and a drizzle of sweet sauce was too darn addictive. The Sweet and Sour Pork was also solid, can feel the slab of lean meat on each piece (i.e. not 30% meat, 40% fat, 30% batter like some places). Also, they are generous on portion and is very wallet friendly.

restaurant name: Nandhana's @ Ang Mo Kio Djitsun mall
content:
6 of us went for a lunch on Saturday. Ordered Chicken Lolly pop and Chicken 65 for starters. Both were really nice and crispy and well flavoured.
For mains.. we ordered Naan and few choice of curries.
The bearer recommended Kongu Naattu Chicken curry and Mutton Nenju elumbu kolombu. We ordered both.. nenju elumbu kolombu was a let down.. overly spiced and the mutton bone pieces were full of koluppu ( fat).. unable to eat.
We also ordered prawn masala and that was an excellent choice to go with Naan.
Overall, taste of most items were very good.
Food served within 5 mins of order .. not seen any restaurant serving food this fast. Excellent!!
Will surely return again.

content:
Had first visited Phoenix at the original location on a few occasions in Bukit Panjang near Phoenix LRT (hence the name?). The homely atmosphere coupled with the personal service from the owners made it a regular 'go to' restaurant. And of course the food, which is why we keep coming back.

Was happy that they moved to a location inside Science Centre, easier accessibility and quicker drive from home! They've got a bigger space now in a more cordial setting, as opposed to the 'industrial feel' location they were in earlier.

The food doesn't disappoint and spice levels were just about nice on the curries we ordered. Not too overpowering and extremely pleasant on the taste buds. Doesn't give you that heavy masala-ish feeling that makes you feel bloated and heavy. So it was very light on the spices which can pull you through a post-lunch meeting without nodding off!

Service was a tad disappointing, probably new staff that needed a bit of training? The lady owner was around and of course very friendly and hospitable as before. But service in general needed some improvement.

The new ambience is nice and a welcome change from the smaller space they had earlier. They also have an extended dining space to cater for a larger crowd, especially on weekends.

Must try item - Bhuna Gosht!

content:
Hi Ichikokudo! Here's my review (Food, Service & Ambience) for my dining experience today:

Food:
Ordered the limited edition Ichi-Mazesoba for a more adventurous palate. Usually would just go for the classic ichikokudo ramen but i wanted to try something different. Totally worth the experience! I loved how the sweetness from the sauce and the tanginess from the vinegar comes together. There is also a variety of texture from the crispy bits and diced onion. Really felt like a party going on in my mouth and it's really worth the try! The best part was the onsen egg, my favourite! It binds all the different elements together and combining it into one. Definitely will be back for this before it runs out!

Service:
The staffs there were really an amazing bunch! Came during the evening time and i will usually expect them to be drained but was otherwise. Welcomed me with great energy, greeted and assisted me generously and politely.

Ambience:
I was seated somewhere near the kitchen and it was nice to hear some chill music playing along. They were pretty soft... which is a bummer because i don't like silent meals but it was nice seeing the people there enjoy their working environment. I must say that most places i've been to, service crews will be just stuck one corner and watching customers as they come and go but for ichikokudo jurong point, the store itself felt alive with the vibrant energy from the staffs. It's pretty calming and enjoyable seeing them love doing what they do and still serve us greatly. It makes my experience here indeed more pleasant!

Overall, i'll be back for the yummy mazesoba and the lively atmosphere there :)
